biggest challenge, most surprising result, what you learned

During the first three lectures of NSC, the most suprising thing i learned is that numpy has a quite large overhead if you do not use it correct. My naive implementation used np.abs(z), where z was the Python complex type, this implementation took 39.858s. However, switching to Python abs(z) resulted in a much faster program, which took just 8.6s. 

The biggest challenge for me was setting up Mamba, as i have experience with most of the packages (NumPy, Numba, cProfile) we have used so far. However, i have never line_profiler, which to me seems quite useful because it is able to show how much time each line of the profiled function takes.

Despite having experience with most of the stuff we have used in the course so far, i feel that i have gotten a much better understanding of how to effectively use these tools. For example, as part of our project we are using KNN with cosine distance and with a lot of neighbours of many dimensions. For one test sample our naive implementation took ~40s, but after adding the @NJIT decorator, adding "prange" and setting parallel=True, it only took 0.125s.

